# Git Conventions

**Config file:** .claude/git-scopes.json -- read this file for current scopes and config before every git operation.

## Commit Format

```
type(scope): subject{{TICKET_FORMAT}}
```

### Allowed Types

- feat
- fix
- refactor
- test
- docs
- ci
- chore

### Allowed Scopes

{{SCOPES_LIST}}

## Branch Format

Use branch format from .claude/git-scopes.json `branch_format` field.
Main branch: `{{MAIN_BRANCH}}`

## Checklist

Before committing:
- [ ] Commit message follows type(scope): subject format
- [ ] Scope is from the allowed scopes list above or from .claude/git-scopes.json
- [ ] No secrets or credentials in the commit
{{CO_AUTHORED_BY_SECTION}}
{{GITMOJI_SECTION}}

## Rules

1. ALWAYS read .claude/git-scopes.json before generating commit messages
2. Use conventional commit format
3. Scope must match one of the defined project scopes
4. Subject line max 72 characters
5. No period at end of subject
6. Use imperative mood in subject line ("add" not "added")

## Examples

```
feat(core): add user authentication
fix(api): handle null response from external service
docs(core): update README with setup instructions
chore(ci): update Node.js version in workflow
```

## Config Reference

The .claude/git-scopes.json file contains:
- `scopes`: array of allowed scope names
- `main_branch`: the main/default branch name
- `branch_format`: template for branch names
- `ticket_prefix`: optional ticket prefix (e.g. "PROJ-")
- `co_authored_by`: whether to include co-authorship attribution in commits
- `types`: allowed commit types
